WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.220
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today, we're&nbsp;
gonna do something rather interesting. We're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.220 --> 00:00:20.010
to take this particle-antiparticle symmetry&nbsp;
that comes from physics and extend it into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.010 --> 00:00:27.630
mathematics. This is going to be essential for&nbsp;
us to be able to use the multiset framework&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:34.200
consistently across the board to set up linear&nbsp;
algebra, field theory, and other things as well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:39.450
including group theory later on. So, in some&nbsp;
ways, what we're going to do now will appear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.450 --> 00:00:44.370
like a game, and you can think about it that&nbsp;
way. It's a kind of a technical device that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.370 --> 00:00:49.290
we're going to introduce that allows us to make&nbsp;
sense of things that we want to write down,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:49.290 --> 00:00:55.140
but because we're obligated to be very precise&nbsp;
about what things actually mean, we actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.140 --> 00:00:59.820
have to identify the objects that correspond&nbsp;
to the things that we want to write down.

00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:07.050
So the story is motivated by this remarkable&nbsp;
discovery of 20th-century physics, going back&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.050 --> 00:01:14.670
to essentially Dirac around 1930, that there was&nbsp;
some kind of strange antiparticle for an electron,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:21.210
which subsequently was called a positron. And&nbsp;
then eventually, physicists realized this was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.210 --> 00:01:26.520
not some kind of isolated occurrence, but was&nbsp;
rather a manifestation of some kind of general&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:33.600
symmetry—that basically every elementary&nbsp;
particle has an associated antiparticle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:41.640
with roughly the same mass but opposite charges.&nbsp;
So not only do we have an electron and positron,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:48.240
but we have a proton and an antiproton,&nbsp;
a neutron and antineutron, a neutrino and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:54.450
antineutrino, an up quark and an anti-up quark,&nbsp;
and so on. Generally, the convention that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.450 --> 00:02:00.870
physicists like to use is that if the particle is&nbsp;
denoted by a b, then the antiparticle is denoted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:07.440
with a b with a bar over it. So there's at least&nbsp;
theoretically some kind of symmetry between these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:14.220
particles and antiparticles that was discovered&nbsp;
by physicists, and now I think they have a kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:21.330
of reasonable explanation for why this one goes&nbsp;
across the board. That's very interesting, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.330 --> 00:02:26.490
we're going to take on board a little bit of that&nbsp;
understanding from the 20th-century physicists.

00:02:26.490 --> 00:02:34.950
So to motivate this, let's recall that one of the&nbsp;
important things that numbers do for us is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:42.840
they allow us to scale existing data structures.&nbsp;
That means that we can multiply, say, M-sets by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:51.150
numbers. So, for example, here is a rather general&nbsp;
M-set. So I'm not being very specific about what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:55.620
objects are in here; these could be any kind of&nbsp;
mathematical objects as long as we've already&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.620 --> 00:03:02.550
had a prior definition of what they are. We'll&nbsp;
just represent them as some kind of objects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.550 --> 00:03:08.250
say heart, heart, diamond. And we want to take&nbsp;
this M-set and we want to multiply it by two.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.250 --> 00:03:14.790
So here is the number two represented by our two&nbsp;
little marks, okay? And we know how to do that:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:20.070
we multiply each one of these marks by each one&nbsp;
of these things. And the basic rule here is that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.070 --> 00:03:25.110
well, mark times a heart is a heart. So we&nbsp;
have a heart, and then we offer another heart,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.110 --> 00:03:33.120
and then we go to this one heart and another&nbsp;
heart, and then a diamond and another diamond. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:40.230
so that's the way we multiply this M-set by this&nbsp;
number. And a special case is what happens when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:48.600
we multiply the same M-set by the number zero or&nbsp;
the empty M-set. Well, in this case, there's a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:54.000
of products of the form emptiness or nothing times&nbsp;
something, and nothing times something is nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:03.270
so we get nothing on the right-hand side. So we&nbsp;
get the empty set again. So this empty set is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.270 --> 00:04:10.290
playing a very generic role here. It's really just&nbsp;
the empty, I should say, empty multiset. It's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.290 --> 00:04:15.930
empty multiset, which can be a number, can be&nbsp;
a natural number, it can be a negative number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:23.310
it can be an integer. We can even think about it&nbsp;
as being a type of M-set of pixels or Maxwells,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.310 --> 00:04:28.350
and so on. So it's a rather general kind of thing&nbsp;
that plays its role in many different situations.

00:04:28.350 --> 00:04:37.500
So now we know how to define n times A if n is&nbsp;
a natural number and A is an M-set, and there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:44.610
a pleasant algebra. Okay, now we want to ask&nbsp;
this question, this natural extension: How do we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.610 --> 00:04:51.720
multiply an M-set by a negative number? How does&nbsp;
that work? Well, it all comes down to specifying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.720 --> 00:05:00.300
what happens when we multiply some generic object&nbsp;
by each of our three basic ingredients of numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.300 --> 00:05:08.310
namely the mark, emptiness, and the anti-mark.&nbsp;
And we've already convinced ourselves that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:16.110
mark times, say, heart ought to be heart, and&nbsp;
that nothing times heart ought to be nothing. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.110 --> 00:05:25.170
now the question is, what should anti-mark times&nbsp;
heart be? Let's temporarily call it heart-bar. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:32.070
we're going to introduce possibly a new kind of&nbsp;
object called heart-bar, which is the result of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.070 --> 00:05:39.900
taking a little anti-mark and multiplying it by&nbsp;
heart, okay? These three rules will then tell us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.900 --> 00:05:48.960
how to multiply our basic elements with a general&nbsp;
generic object, and that will then allow us to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:57.150
extend our multiplication of numbers times M-sets&nbsp;
to a very general situation. We'll now be able to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.150 --> 00:06:03.690
multiply any number, be it a negative number&nbsp;
or a natural number, by an arbitrary M-set.

00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:11.610
Okay, so what about this new object that we're&nbsp;
introducing? Well, it has to have a very special&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.610 --> 00:06:19.200
property. So we require that this new object,&nbsp;
heart-bar, has the property that it cancels with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:27.360
heart—that heart together with heart-bar gives&nbsp;
us nothing. And this is an equation that has to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:33.690
happen inside an M-set. So, you know, if we have&nbsp;
an M-set and it contains a heart somewhere and it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:38.130
also contains a heart-bar or an anti-heart,&nbsp;
then those two things are going to cancel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:47.790
just the way a neutron and an antineutron cancel,&nbsp;
and the result is nothing. So that's the property&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.790 --> 00:06:55.440
that this new object has to have, that it has&nbsp;
to cancel with this one. And why is that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:59.850
the reason is the following: that&nbsp;
if we take zero times an M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.850 --> 00:07:07.650
we should get zero or the empty M-set. And so&nbsp;
if you take the empty M-set and we multiply,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:12.960
say, by the single M-set containing just a heart,&nbsp;
whatever that might be, then we know we should get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:20.970
an empty M-set. But we also know that this empty&nbsp;
M-set, or the number zero, is in some sense the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.970 --> 00:07:26.220
same as the M-set consisting of a mark and an&nbsp;
anti-mark together, because we know that that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:33.330
mark and the anti-mark cancel to give us emptiness&nbsp;
or nothing. So what would happen if we consider&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:41.280
this product here by the usual rule? So we just&nbsp;
multiply the mark times a heart—there it is—and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:48.870
we multiply the anti-mark times a heart. Now we&nbsp;
know that the mark times a heart is heart, and so,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.870 --> 00:07:56.640
well, we're going to get this new M-set is heart,&nbsp;
and the other one is anti-mark times heart. Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.640 --> 00:08:04.200
this supposedly is going to be the empty M-set, so&nbsp;
for this to work, we require that this new object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:12.030
anti-mark times heart, which is what we're calling&nbsp;
heart-bar or anti-heart, that that object has the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:17.790
property, this cancellation property, that when&nbsp;
we have a heart and this anti-heart together,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.790 --> 00:08:25.650
they better cancel to give us the empty&nbsp;
M-set. In other words, inside the M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:31.830
we want this crucial cancellation&nbsp;
that heart times heart-bar is nothing.

00:08:31.830 --> 00:08:38.340
So we're really proposing something&nbsp;
that's quite dramatically new here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.340 --> 00:08:47.360
even though it's a little bit formal and technical&nbsp;
and maybe so out of the vision most of the time.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:54.110
But nevertheless, theoretically, it really changes&nbsp;
the landscape of mathematics. So I remind you that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.110 --> 00:08:59.450
our basic premise is that we are going to build&nbsp;
up mathematical objects from the bottom up, right?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.450 --> 00:09:05.570
That's our basic orientation. We're starting at&nbsp;
the bottom, not already assuming all kinds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.570 --> 00:09:12.080
stuff, and we're building things up step by step,&nbsp;
one at a time, and going from simpler structures&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:18.410
to more complicated structures to more complicated&nbsp;
structures. And now what we're proposing is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.410 --> 00:09:24.200
we're going to have this general orientation&nbsp;
that for any bona fide mathematical object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:29.780
heart—so, some process in this building up, we&nbsp;
get some object that we're very comfortable with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.780 --> 00:09:36.320
let's call it heart—okay, that we're going&nbsp;
to propose that there is another object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:41.660
kind of a mirror object, actually an&nbsp;
anti-object that corresponds to that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:48.530
that object, which is its anti-object. In&nbsp;
other words, there's going to be a new object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.530 --> 00:09:55.370
heart-bar, which we can define as the anti-mark&nbsp;
times the heart that we're considering,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.370 --> 00:09:59.180
that has this crucial cancellation&nbsp;
property that we've seen several times.

00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:09.350
So we want this to be true across the board&nbsp;
in the same way as the particle-antiparticle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:09.350 --> 00:10:16.370
duality works across the board for elementary&nbsp;
physics. It's not just electron and positron&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:16.370 --> 00:10:23.270
or proton and antiproton. This is a general&nbsp;
kind of symmetry that's going to apply to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.270 --> 00:10:29.270
any kind of legitimate mathematical&nbsp;
object that we're able to construct.

00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:38.180
And some definition or terminology: So, let's&nbsp;
say if the object that we're considering happens&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:45.350
to be the object called heart, then we'll&nbsp;
call this thing here anti-heart and we'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:45.350 --> 00:10:52.580
say that anti-heart is the anti of heart.&nbsp;
So I'm introducing this usage of this word&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.580 --> 00:10:57.740
in a slightly different way. So this is&nbsp;
supposed to be similar to the use of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:04.810
word opposite—the opposite of black is white,&nbsp;
the opposite of day is night. Now we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.810 --> 00:11:11.260
to talk about the anti of a mathematical&nbsp;
object, heart, as being this thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:20.650
anti-heart, or we'll say heart-bar when we're&nbsp;
sort of talking about how we write it down. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:20.650 --> 00:11:30.610
the anti of a mark is the anti-mark. The anti&nbsp;
of the anti-mark—how do we get that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:30.610 --> 00:11:33.520
the definition is always the same: the&nbsp;
anti of something is what you get when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:36.700
you take the anti-mark and multiply&nbsp;
it by that something. In this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:42.850
we know what we get. We take the anti-mark and&nbsp;
we multiply it by the anti-mark. Anti-mark times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:42.850 --> 00:11:48.130
anti-mark—we've decided already that that's going&nbsp;
to be the mark. So this crucial property that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:48.130 --> 00:11:58.780
anti of the anti-mark is just the mark. So I do&nbsp;
admit that this takes some getting used to, may&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:05.650
take a little while for this to sort of sink into&nbsp;
our consciousness, but it's pretty interesting,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:05.650 --> 00:12:12.310
and we'll see that it's really essential to be&nbsp;
able to do the kinds of things that we want to do.

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:20.950
So what is this anti of something? Is the anti&nbsp;
of a number just its negative? No, it's not,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:20.950 --> 00:12:28.630
okay? The anti of a number is not its negative.&nbsp;
The anti of a number is a new kind of object. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:33.610
for example, here is the number that we&nbsp;
usually call four. It's an M-set with mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.610 --> 00:12:40.240
mark, mark, mark in it. It's a natural number.&nbsp;
So the anti of this thing, what is it? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:44.440
this is a mathematical object, and its&nbsp;
anti is what you get when you multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:50.560
it by anti-mark. And by definition, that's&nbsp;
just a new object that has a bar over it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.560 --> 00:12:56.830
okay? So, as if we really do anything, we just&nbsp;
take that object and we put a bar over it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:56.830 --> 00:13:03.070
and then it's some new object, the anti of what&nbsp;
we had previously. So there's the object here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:08.050
and notice that the bar goes right over all of it.&nbsp;
So we're taking the bar over the whole thing, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:08.050 --> 00:13:14.830
if we were going to write this as a hint of Arabic&nbsp;
numeral four, then we would just write four-bar.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:14.830 --> 00:13:22.600
And what kind of a new thing is this? Well, it&nbsp;
makes sense to say that the type of this thing is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:22.600 --> 00:13:30.100
anti-net. This is a net, so this is an anti-net.&nbsp;
And what property does this have? Well, if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:30.100 --> 00:13:36.370
take an M-set consisting of this and four-bar,&nbsp;
there's four, and there's four-bar or anti-four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:42.070
then those two things are going to cancel. That's&nbsp;
the basic cancellation, and I'm going to get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:42.070 --> 00:13:50.980
the empty set or zero. On the other hand, minus&nbsp;
four, okay, minus four also involves anti-things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:50.980 --> 00:13:57.520
but minus four was the M-set consisting of four&nbsp;
anti-marks—anti-mark, anti-mark, anti-mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:03.340
anti-mark. That's a negative number. That's&nbsp;
actually quite different. So this is different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.340 --> 00:14:10.840
from this. If you like, here the bar extends over&nbsp;
the whole thing, and here we're just having the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:16.720
individual elements inside the M-set being barred.&nbsp;
So this is not equal to this; they're different.

00:14:16.720 --> 00:14:22.750
So, for example, if we make an M-set containing&nbsp;
the number four and the number minus four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:22.750 --> 00:14:29.500
then we're not going to get zero; we're not&nbsp;
going to get the empty M-set because these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:35.020
two things don't cancel themselves out as&nbsp;
objects. This is now a new M-set which has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:38.800
two elements in it. One of the elements is&nbsp;
four, and the other element is minus four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:38.800 --> 00:14:44.200
and that's just what it is. It doesn't&nbsp;
simplify to anything simpler. But if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:53.800
have four and anti-four, you are obliged&nbsp;
to cancel those object pairs and simplify.

00:14:53.800 --> 00:15:00.700
So let me give you some motivation for why&nbsp;
we want to do this. Anti-objects allow us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:09.400
to introduce negative numbers into vexels and&nbsp;
maxels. Here, for example, is a vexel. It is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:14.620
an M-set consisting of singletons: the singleton&nbsp;
two, the singleton zero, the singleton minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:14.620 --> 00:15:22.060
the singleton one, the singleton one. And so&nbsp;
these are singletons from integers. That means&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:22.060 --> 00:15:30.730
they are lists whose elements are integers—just&nbsp;
a list with one element. And we know that we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:30.730 --> 00:15:37.420
represent this kind of thing in a sort of vector&nbsp;
form by recording the number of zeros we have,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:43.330
the number of ones we have, and the number of&nbsp;
minus ones we have. We can write this down in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:43.330 --> 00:15:48.610
a freeze kind of fashion like that, with this&nbsp;
convention that the zero spot is identified by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.610 --> 00:16:00.850
some bar, so we know where it's sort of centered.&nbsp;
Here's another kind of vexel, but now this is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.850 --> 00:16:10.570
new kind of object because it has not just&nbsp;
singletons, but also some anti-singletons.

00:16:10.570 --> 00:16:19.090
So let's try to get our heads around this,&nbsp;
okay? What do we see in this M-set? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.090 --> 00:16:26.830
how about zero singletons? How many&nbsp;
zero singletons are there here? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:26.830 --> 00:16:33.790
there is not really ten singletons;&nbsp;
there's minus one singleton because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:33.790 --> 00:16:39.070
this anti-singleton zero counts as minus&nbsp;
one of them. That's what we're going to do;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:39.070 --> 00:16:46.450
we're going to interpret this anti-object as&nbsp;
minus one of the original object. So we see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:46.450 --> 00:16:50.770
that there's one anti-singleton zero here,&nbsp;
so we're going to record that by putting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:50.770 --> 00:16:57.550
a minus one in the zero spot. In terms of&nbsp;
minus one singletons, there's two of them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:57.550 --> 00:17:07.390
so we'll put a two in the minus one spot. And&nbsp;
also, in the two spot, up here is a singleton two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:07.390 --> 00:17:15.400
only one of them, so we'll put a one there. But in&nbsp;
the singleton one spot, we have singleton one-bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:26.080
singleton one-bar—that corresponds to minus two&nbsp;
singleton ones. So we would put a minus two there.

00:17:26.080 --> 00:17:31.750
So let me try to convince you that this&nbsp;
actually makes sense, that this is consistent,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:31.750 --> 00:17:37.210
this is logical. Because suppose you wanted to add&nbsp;
these two vectors, okay? These are M-sets, so we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:42.920
know how to add M-sets. We just put them together.&nbsp;
So V + W, so we take all of these elements, just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:42.920 --> 00:17:48.860
put them in there, and then we add all of these&nbsp;
elements, starting from here. There we go. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:48.860 --> 00:17:54.590
now we have this big M-set. And now we look at&nbsp;
it and say, "Well, wait a minute, there is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:54.590 --> 00:18:04.070
singleton zero here and there is its anti-object."&nbsp;
Like, there's the anti of this. So this thing and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:04.070 --> 00:18:13.760
this thing cancel—poof, they're gone, replaced&nbsp;
with nothing. And now there's only this singleton&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:23.870
zero left. How about minus ones? Well, there's one&nbsp;
minus one singleton there, and there's another one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:29.600
there, another one there, so altogether there's&nbsp;
three of them. How about the one singletons? So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:36.140
there's one here, one here, and one here,&nbsp;
but here there's an anti on one of these,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:36.140 --> 00:18:41.900
and here there's another anti on one of these.&nbsp;
So this anti cancels with one of these; we don't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:41.900 --> 00:18:46.580
really care which one—this one here—they cancel.&nbsp;
This one cancels with another one—say, that one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:55.370
there—and we're left with a single singleton one.&nbsp;
And the singleton two is alone, finds over there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:55.370 --> 00:19:01.670
it's just there. And then when we count what we&nbsp;
have left over, well, we have one singleton zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:10.820
we have three singleton minus ones, and we have&nbsp;
singleton one and a singleton two. And we see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:10.820 --> 00:19:17.420
that this is indeed what we expect in terms&nbsp;
of component-wise addition of these vectors&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:17.420 --> 00:19:23.630
over here. So there's a zero spot, so two plus&nbsp;
minus one is indeed one. One plus two is three,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:33.980
three plus minus two is one, zero plus one is one.&nbsp;
So these minus ones here are representing these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:33.980 --> 00:19:42.260
anti-objects, and they add to the original objects&nbsp;
in the right way; namely, they cancel with them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:42.260 --> 00:19:52.180
in the multiset, so we get the correct additive&nbsp;
structure on the vector side of things. The price&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.180 --> 00:19:57.370
we pay is that in order to have minus ones,&nbsp;
where we want to interpret those minus ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:57.370 --> 00:20:03.400
as multiplicities, we're going to interpret&nbsp;
them as being multiplicities of anti-objects.

00:20:03.400 --> 00:20:08.110
I guess it goes back to, you know, the question,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:08.110 --> 00:20:14.590
what is minus three cows? What does it mean to&nbsp;
take four cows and add minus three cows? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:14.590 --> 00:20:21.370
it's hard to do that physically. You have to&nbsp;
imagine a minus cow, some kind of fictitious&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:21.370 --> 00:20:28.930
object representing some debt. It's not really the&nbsp;
same as a tangible physical cow, but it's a debt,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:28.930 --> 00:20:35.860
it's some kind of virtual object. That's sort of&nbsp;
what we're doing here; we're being more precise&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:35.860 --> 00:20:41.710
about these virtual objects and giving them&nbsp;
names and these bars over them. Basically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:41.710 --> 00:20:46.600
we're doing the same kind of thing: four&nbsp;
cows plus minus three cows gives us one cow,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:46.600 --> 00:20:54.310
four objects plus three anti-objects give&nbsp;
us one object of that particular kind.

00:20:54.310 --> 00:20:59.890
So here's another example of how we can use this&nbsp;
concept for something that's very important for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:59.890 --> 00:21:05.950
us, which is to develop maxel theory in a kind of&nbsp;
a very good arithmetic way. So here's an example&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:05.950 --> 00:21:13.510
of a new kind of maxel. It's got pixels in it, but&nbsp;
some of the pixels are kind of anti-pixels instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:13.510 --> 00:21:19.150
of regular pixels. So we have minus one, two, and&nbsp;
there's a couple of them. We have a zero, one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:19.150 --> 00:21:27.490
but that's an anti-object at zero, two of them.&nbsp;
And we have three of these anti-one, one pixels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:27.490 --> 00:21:33.160
okay? So this is a maxel with both pixels and&nbsp;
what we might call anti-pixels. Obvious what we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:33.160 --> 00:21:38.500
mean by that, right? That's an anti-pixel,&nbsp;
that's a pixel, okay? And we can represent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:49.180
this thing now, and here's our integer screen, a&nbsp;
representation where we have our lines like this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.180 --> 00:21:55.660
There prominently in the middle is our zero,&nbsp;
zero spot. That's the basic reference frame,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:55.660 --> 00:22:01.750
okay? So we would put multiplicities here.&nbsp;
So minus one, two—that's minus one, two. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:01.750 --> 00:22:08.350
that two there represents these two fellows here.&nbsp;
This zero, one—so the zero, one is that position,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:08.350 --> 00:22:16.750
but we don't have one of them; we have basically&nbsp;
minus one of them because there's an anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.750 --> 00:22:21.970
one pixel there, not a regular zero, one pixel.&nbsp;
So we put a minus one there; that minus one is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:21.970 --> 00:22:28.630
a representation of the fact that we have an&nbsp;
anti-pixel there. We have two of these pixels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:28.630 --> 00:22:33.460
the zero, two pixels, so we put two there,&nbsp;
and then we have three of these anti-pixels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:33.460 --> 00:22:42.550
so we put a minus three in the one, one position.&nbsp;
So this is a representation of this M-set which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:42.550 --> 00:22:49.810
contains both pixels and anti-pixels now.&nbsp;
And it's very important for us to be able&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:49.810 --> 00:22:59.020
to do this because we want to do arithmetic with&nbsp;
maxels, but we for sure want to have integers in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:59.020 --> 00:23:06.370
the maxel positions. So we basically want to&nbsp;
do standard linear algebra; we don't want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:06.370 --> 00:23:11.140
just restrict ourselves to natural number&nbsp;
entries in all our matrices and maxels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:11.140 --> 00:23:16.900
because we are always thinking in terms of them&nbsp;
as being M-sets, and if they were M-sets, then the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:16.900 --> 00:23:22.420
multiplicities would always have to be positive.&nbsp;
So we want to free ourselves from that. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:22.420 --> 00:23:28.570
exactly what we've done. We've enlarged our point&nbsp;
of view, admittedly by introducing these strange&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:28.570 --> 00:23:35.800
new anti-objects, but now we're in a position to&nbsp;
interpret very precisely what something like this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:43.960
means in a multiset framework. So these numbers&nbsp;
are still representing multiplicities of objects.

00:23:43.960 --> 00:23:50.860
Now, in certain areas of mathematics, somewhat&nbsp;
more sophisticated mathematics, negative numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:58.480
of objects are introduced by what are sometimes&nbsp;
referred to as formal linear combinations. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:58.480 --> 00:24:03.940
for example, in group theory, maybe you have a&nbsp;
group, a finite group, and it has elements g1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:10.600
g2, g3, g4, and so on. In some situations, it's&nbsp;
useful to consider linear combinations of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:10.600 --> 00:24:19.090
things. For example, we like to do arithmetic&nbsp;
with combinations like 3g1 - 2g2 + 2g3, and it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:19.090 --> 00:24:24.880
a legitimate question to ask, what exactly are we&nbsp;
talking about here? And in traditional algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:24.880 --> 00:24:31.750
there's a little bit of dodging and weaving when&nbsp;
it comes to saying exactly how one sets up such&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.750 --> 00:24:36.520
formal combinations. One usually does something&nbsp;
like this as well: we're considering some formal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:36.520 --> 00:24:41.590
combination, and so on. So what we're doing here&nbsp;
is trying to be more precise about what's really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:50.230
going on when we consider a formal object like&nbsp;
this. What we're proposing here is that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:50.230 --> 00:24:56.080
thing here is really probably living in a multiset&nbsp;
framework, okay? We're talking about a multiset,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:56.080 --> 00:25:01.240
really, that's what this represents,&nbsp;
where there are three g1's, a single g3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:01.240 --> 00:25:12.220
and two anti-g2's. If we have a notion of an&nbsp;
anti-object, that makes perfect sense, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:12.220 --> 00:25:18.220
we have a consistent multiset interpretation of&nbsp;
this kind of formal combination that's going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:18.220 --> 00:25:25.690
be useful in quite a lot of contexts. So this&nbsp;
object-anti-object setup is an alternative to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:25.690 --> 00:25:32.230
some more loose kind of discussion that one&nbsp;
often finds in advanced algebra courses.

00:25:32.230 --> 00:25:37.780
Now, a curious aspect of the&nbsp;
20th-century physicists' understanding of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:37.780 --> 00:25:42.910
particle-antiparticles is that although there's&nbsp;
this theoretical symmetry, practically, if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:42.910 --> 00:25:47.200
look out there in the real world, you do not see&nbsp;
a symmetry between particles and antiparticles.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:54.070
Pretty well everything in our ordinary world&nbsp;
consists of just particles, and the antiparticles&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:54.070 --> 00:26:02.560
of things in our world are very hard to find.&nbsp;
That's why they weren't observed until 1930. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:08.260
there's definitely an asymmetry with regard to&nbsp;
the prevalence of particles and antiparticles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:08.260 --> 00:26:17.920
at least in this neck of the woods where we are&nbsp;
here in our universe. Okay, so similarly, we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:17.920 --> 00:26:23.800
going to find that we're going to use anti-objects&nbsp;
rather minimally. It's not as if now, suddenly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:29.890
our mathematics is going to be populated by all&nbsp;
kinds of anti-things. Rather, this is a sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:29.890 --> 00:26:38.530
technical device that allows us to justify putting&nbsp;
negative numbers in lists that are multiplicity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:38.530 --> 00:26:49.360
lists for M-sets. So it's a way of still doing our&nbsp;
arithmetic but in a more general way, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:49.360 --> 00:26:57.310
in a kind of formally correct way. Because we're&nbsp;
going to be rather general about being able to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:57.310 --> 00:27:02.560
take an anti of something, it might be that&nbsp;
the objects like heart that we're considering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:02.560 --> 00:27:08.710
might be actually quite long objects. We could be&nbsp;
considering an M-set with three thousand things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:08.710 --> 00:27:17.110
and we might want to take its anti. So we will&nbsp;
use this notation that anti-mark times heart&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:17.110 --> 00:27:23.170
is heart-bar, with the bar right over the heart.&nbsp;
But sometimes we will also allow ourselves this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:23.170 --> 00:27:31.030
alternate usage where we put the little bar to&nbsp;
the right, almost like an index, okay? So imagine&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:31.030 --> 00:27:36.640
if this is some big M-set that's very long; we'll&nbsp;
just stick the bar at the end, sort of over at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:44.020
end of the final bracket, just so we don't have&nbsp;
to write some big overline. So, for example, here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:44.020 --> 00:27:52.330
this is an M-set. It's actually a maxel, it's got&nbsp;
three pixels. So it's possible for us to consider&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:52.330 --> 00:28:01.330
the anti of a maxel, and instead of writing&nbsp;
this, we could alternately just write the maxel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:01.330 --> 00:28:11.650
with a prominent bar at the end on the right as an&nbsp;
index there. So that means the anti of this maxel.

00:28:11.650 --> 00:28:19.210
So in our next video, I do want to say a&nbsp;
little bit more about this anti operation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:19.210 --> 00:28:23.980
It's obviously a kind of a novel and interesting&nbsp;
thing, and there's a few more things to say about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:23.980 --> 00:28:28.960
it. And then after that, we'll get on&nbsp;
to some very interesting applications to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:30.140 --> 00:28:35.360
setting up field theory and higher arithmetic,&nbsp;
really from the maxel point of view. But next&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:42.200
time, a little bit more about this curious&nbsp;
anti operation that we've now introduced into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:42.200 --> 00:28:47.180
mathematics. Hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
going Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

